            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title">MS III Second Poetry Anthology</head>
                <!--An apparatus may contain all or only some of the following sections.-->
                <div type="section" xml:id="WITNESSES">
                    <head type="section">Witnesses</head>
                    <list type="simple">
                        <item>&#x201C;The Constellations: Northern, Some of the Zodiac, and
                            Some of the Southern&#x201D;;</item>
                        <item>&#x201C;Time: Blank Verse&#x201D;;</item>
                        <item>&#x201C;The Sun&#x201D;;</item>
                        <item>&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Papa how
                            pretty those icicles are&#x201D;);</item>
                        <item>&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1827];</item>
                        <item>&#x201C;The British Battles.&#x201D;</item>
                    </list>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>Ruskin entitled the collection &#x201C;<hi rend="caps"
                        >Poetry</hi>,&#x201D; just as he had headed the MS I Poetry Anthology
                        as &#x201C;Poetry&#x201D;.</p>
                </div>
                <!--<div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>-->
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
                    <div type="section" xml:id="CONTENTS">
                        <head type="section">Contents</head>
                        <p>The anthology contains the following poems, in order of their appearance:</p>
                        <list type="ordered">
                            <item>&#x201C;The Constellations: Northern, Some of the Zodiac, and
                                Some of the Southern&#x201D;;</item>
                            <item>&#x201C;Time: Blank Verse&#x201D;;</item>
                            <item>&#x201C;The Sun&#x201D;;</item>
                            <item>&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Papa how
                                pretty those icicles are&#x201D;);</item>
                            <item>&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1827];</item>
                            <item>&#x201C;The British Battles.&#x201D;</item>
                        </list>
                    </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p>Ruskin compiled this anthology in MS III in 1828, sometime after New
                        Year&#x02BC;s Day, making it the second anthology in this Red Book, after
                        Poetry Descriptive (1827) (see MS III: Discussion; see also MS III Third Poetry
                        Anthology).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPILATION">
                    <head type="section">Compilation</head>
                    <p>A drawing, Ship and House, [Miscellaneous Drawing, MS III], falls within the
                        anthology, and probably predates it. Ruskin probably intended the drawing to
                        illustrate &#x201C;Harry and Lucy,&#x201D; Vol. 2, but, ending the
                        narrative earlier than expected, wrapped the drawing round by &#x201C;Time:
                        Blank Verse.&#x201D; Another drawing, &#x201C;Ragland Castle When
                        Newly Built,&#x201D; [Miscellaneous Drawing, MS III], forms the terminus of
                        the anthology and, again, probably predates it, but this drawing can be dated
                        less securely (see MS III: Discussion; MS III Drawings).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="THEMES">
                    <head type="section">Themes</head>
                    <p><p>See Poetry Descriptive for W. G. Collingwood&#x02BC;s assumption that this
                        collection along with the second form a single anthology. Of the second
                        anthology, however, only &#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D;
                        (&#x201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x201D;) is
                        &#x201C;descriptive&#x201D; in the topographical sense of the earlier
                        collection, the second being dominated more by catalog poetry and New
                        Year&#x02BC;s poetry.</p></p>
